  "enhanced_information": "Cardiac muscle primarily utilizes fatty acids as its main energy source under normal conditions, as they are abundant in the bloodstream and undergo beta-oxidation to produce ATP. However, cardiac muscle is also capable of utilizing ketone bodies and glucose, especially during periods of fasting or increased demand. Ketone bodies are converted to acetyl-CoA, which enters the Krebs cycle, while glucose is metabolized through glycolysis to pyruvate, which is also converted to acetyl-CoA. All three substrates can effectively produce ATP, demonstrating the adaptability of cardiac muscle to different energy sources. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Any of the above' (option d), as all three sources contribute to energy production in cardiac muscle under normal physiological conditions."
